WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.440
[Music] Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger, and&nbsp;
in this part of our series on mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:19.480
foundations, we're going to look at how to&nbsp;
visualize the rational numbers and introduce&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:26.240
one of the 20th century's most remarkable&nbsp;
discoveries: something called Ford circles.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:35.520
Okay, so we've introduced the rational numbers&nbsp;
as pairs of integers, but we haven't explained&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:40.840
how to visualize these things. So here's a very&nbsp;
nice way of thinking about them. First of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:47.320
we start in the plane where we have&nbsp;
an x-axis with integer values and a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:54.240
y-axis with integer values. That allows us&nbsp;
to identify a pair of integers with a point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.240 --> 00:01:01.240
one of these integer lattice points in the plane.&nbsp;
There are an infinite number of them, and here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:10.040
is the origin. We imagine ourselves at the origin&nbsp;
looking out at this integer lattice, like stars in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:20.440
the night sky. If we look in this direction here,&nbsp;
say towards (3,2), then behind this one is (6,4),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:25.840
and behind that would be (9,6). If we look&nbsp;
in the corresponding opposite direction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:34.200
we would have (-3,-2) and so on. Since we're&nbsp;
equating 3/2 with 6/4, these are the same rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:42.840
numbers. It follows that this line represents that&nbsp;
rational number, and so a rational number, in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:51.360
point of view, is nothing but a line through the&nbsp;
origin through some integer point in this lattice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:57.160
with a slight exception. The exception is that&nbsp;
this line here is not included because that would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.160 --> 00:02:05.000
correspond to a fraction or a rational number&nbsp;
of the form k/0, and that's not allowed. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:13.960
all lines except for the horizontal one that go&nbsp;
through the origin constitute rational numbers.

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:19.440
Now let's connect that with a more standard&nbsp;
way of thinking about it. We're looking here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:27.280
at the line where y is equal to 1, okay?&nbsp;
That's above the x-axis, a unit one above,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:35.480
and our line through (3,2), which represents the&nbsp;
rational number 3/2, intersects this red line at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:44.760
that point right there. That's the point&nbsp;
whose x-coordinate is 3/2. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:51.160
where this line intersects the red line&nbsp;
is where we usually think of the rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:58.360
number as sitting on a number line. So in&nbsp;
this formulation of things, we do not want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:03.680
this to be the rational number line; we rather&nbsp;
want this line here, which is one unit up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:08.400
to be the rational number line. So we think&nbsp;
of this as being the integer number line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:14.400
and we think of this as being the rational number&nbsp;
line. Any rational number corresponds to a line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:20.280
and that line intersects the red line somewhere,&nbsp;
and that's the actual rational number in the usual&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:28.800
sense represented by that line. So a rational&nbsp;
number is a line through the origin and an integer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.800 --> 00:03:35.640
point (m,n) which is not horizontal. This gives&nbsp;
us a very physical, visualizable understanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:41.400
of what rational numbers are. Moreover, it&nbsp;
connects with these remarkable Ford circles.

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:46.640
I'm now going to tell you about Ford circles,&nbsp;
which were introduced or discovered by Lester&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:55.040
Ford in an article in 1938, just before World War&nbsp;
II, in the American Mathematical Monthly. It was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.040 --> 00:04:00.720
a remarkable discovery that connects with so many&nbsp;
things and gives us a lovely further insight into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:07.920
the nature and complexity of the rational number&nbsp;
system. Here's what we do: I'm going to look at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.920 --> 00:04:14.840
that rational number strip that we had in the&nbsp;
previous slide but in a blown-up way. So here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.840 --> 00:04:24.000
our ordinary integer number line, the x-axis: 0,&nbsp;
1, 2, -1, and so on. And here is the line y=1. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:30.000
this is level y=1, that's the line that we had&nbsp;
in red in the previous picture. What I do is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:37.880
for every integer point or for every integer&nbsp;
rational number, I draw a circle of diameter one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:47.520
So it fits exactly in here, and these circles,&nbsp;
each one for every integer rational number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:52.120
they all fit together nicely, touching&nbsp;
each other and touching the line y=1.

00:04:55.240 --> 00:05:00.120
Now what we're going to do is we're going&nbsp;
to set other circles on top of the circles&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:05.360
that we already have. So between these circles&nbsp;
here, we're going to position another circle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:12.560
which is tangent to the two circles we already&nbsp;
have and just touches our line y=1. Then it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:19.520
obviously by symmetry going to meet this line&nbsp;
at the place where the x-coordinate is 1/2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:30.160
and it turns out (by a nice computation) that&nbsp;
the diameter of this circle is exactly 1/4. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:34.560
can visualize that by imagining a small&nbsp;
bubble. We drop a little bubble in here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:39.040
and we allow that bubble to grow, always&nbsp;
touching the two circles we already have,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:46.120
until it finally touches the top of the&nbsp;
surface of the water. At that point, it stops.

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:50.440
For example, after we've gotten that one there,&nbsp;
we can repeat this procedure. We could drop a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:57.040
bubble in on this side; then it would be tangent&nbsp;
to the circle 1/2 and the circle 1, and it would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:02.480
grow until it reached up there, and then it&nbsp;
would be that green circle there. Similarly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:06.520
if we drop the bubble in here and allowed it&nbsp;
to grow, we would get that one there. And so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:13.840
we can do that anywhere along, and in this&nbsp;
way, we get a successive sequence of circles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:23.680
each one tangent to two previous ones and to the&nbsp;
top line. These circles are called Ford circles.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.680 --> 00:06:27.800
Actually, the usual formulation has them down&nbsp;
here, so it's symmetrically opposite, but it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:27.800 --> 00:06:33.760
convenient for some purposes, for many purposes,&nbsp;
to think of them the way I've drawn them here.

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:40.320
There are a few remarkable facts that happen.&nbsp;
The first remarkable fact is that every rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:49.080
number appears as the top of one of these&nbsp;
Ford circles. So if we keep doing this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:54.280
eventually every rational number,&nbsp;
even very obscure ones with huge&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:59.360
denominators and numerators, will appear&nbsp;
as the top of one Ford circle exactly.

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:24.280
Another interesting fact is that we can&nbsp;
say exactly what the rational number that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:32.440
corresponds to a Ford circle is if we know the&nbsp;
two Ford circles that it touches. Here's the rule:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:42.640
Between m/n and p/q, the Ford circle&nbsp;
is (m+p)/(n+q). This is not the sum of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.640 --> 00:07:47.760
these two rational numbers; it's a new kind of&nbsp;
operation. You just add the numerators, and you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:54.080
add the denominators. That's called the mediant&nbsp;
of these two rational numbers. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:54.080 --> 00:08:03.040
this one here is touching 1/2 and touching 1,&nbsp;
so it's obtained by adding 1+1 over adding 2+1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:12.080
which is 2/3. This one here would be 2+1&nbsp;
over 3+1, which is 3/4. It's remarkable.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:20.280
Finally, two touching Ford circles, for example,&nbsp;
the ones at 2/3 and the one at 3/4, have the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:30.280
property that when you look at these numbers, they&nbsp;
have a special relation: 24 - 33 is either plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:38.840
or minus one. So these two rational numbers are&nbsp;
as close as they can be without being equal. If&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:45.800
they were equal, then this would be zero, so they&nbsp;
are as close as they can be without being equal.

00:08:45.800 --> 00:08:52.200
Ford circles have interesting connections with&nbsp;
hyperbolic geometry, as we'll eventually see,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:58.520
but it's a lovely geometrical visualization.&nbsp;
It shows us that we can think about rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.520 --> 00:09:07.400
numbers as a sort of sequence of increasing&nbsp;
complexity. As the denominators become bigger,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:13.200
the corresponding Ford circles become smaller,&nbsp;
and there's this froth of ever-increasing and more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:20.160
complicated and smaller rational numbers&nbsp;
between the ones that we already have.

00:09:20.160 --> 00:09:25.000
Next time, I want to talk about a&nbsp;
summary of what we've done so far&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:31.360
and how it affects mathematics education. I&nbsp;
hope you're going to join me for that. I'm&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:42.000
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for [Music] listening.

